Before we begin, I want you to know that anything you say here will be kept private between the two of us. The only exception would be if I think you are at immediate risk of harming yourself or somebody else. Then, I would want to involve others who could help keep you safe. Do you have any questions about this?

We know that drinking or drug use above certain levels can cause problems in people's lives. Motivational Interviewing is an intervention that helps people understand these problems and think through the pros and cons of their substance use without a commitment to make a change.

Today, I would like to ask you a few questions about your drug and alcohol use and have a conversation about these results. This conversation will last for about one hour. What do you think about this idea? Do you have any questions?
Now I am going to ask you some questions about your use of alcoholic beverages during the past year.
How often do you have a drink containing alcohol?
On average, how many days per week do you drink alcohol?
How many (standard) drinks containing alcohol do you have on a typical day when you are drinking?
How often do you have six or more drinks on one occasion?
How often during the last year have you found that you were not able to stop drinking once you had started?
How often during the last year have you failed to do what was normally expected from you because of drinking?
How often during the last year have you needed a first drink in the morning to get yourself going after a heavy drinking session?
How often during the last year have you had a feeling of guilt or remorse after drinking?
How often during the last year have you been unable to remember what happened the night before because of your drinking?
Have you or someone else been injured as a result of your drinking?

item.text: I am going to ask you some questions about your potential involvement with drugs, excluding alcohol and tobacco, during the past 12 months.
Have you used drugs other than those required for medical reasons?
Do you use more than one drug at a time?
Are you always able to stop using drugs when you want to?
Have you had "blackouts" or "flashbacks" as a result of drug use?
Do you ever feel bad or guilty about your drug use?
Does your spouse (or parents) ever complain about your involvement with drugs?
Have you neglected your family because of your use of drugs?
Have you engaged in illegal activities in order to obtain drugs?
Have you ever experienced withdrawal symptoms (felt sick) when you stopped taking drugs?
Have you had medical problems as a result of your drug use (e.g., memory loss, hepatitis, convulsions, bleeding etc.)?

In your life, which of the following other drugs have you ever used:

Tip
Thank the client for answering questions and ask for permission to review results on the next few screens.

Example dialogue
"Thank you for taking the time to answer these questions. It really helps me better understand your health. Is it okay if I review these results with you?"

Example dialogue explaining low risk
"On this screen there are different risk levels. At the bottom and in green is the category of low risk, meaning that alcohol and drug use is likely not at a level that hurts the individual's body or negatively affects their life. Green is the largest category because most people are low risk and do not drink or use drugs at all or very frequently."

Example dialogue explaining medium risk
"As you move up the pyramid, you see another category in yellow, which means medium risk. People who score in this range may drink or use drugs more than is recommended on a daily or weekly basis."

Example dialogue explaining high risk
"As you continue to move up the pyramid, you will see another category in red, which means high risk. People who score in this range may drink alcohol or use drugs more than experts recommend. They often say that alcohol or drugs negatively affects different areas of their lives and may experience symptoms of addiction, such as having withdrawal."

Example dialogue
"Do you have any questions about these categories of risk?"

High Risk
  •   Alcohol use likely has a large impact on health
  •   May experience negative effects of drinking
  •   At great risk for health or social problems related to drinking

Medium Risk
  •   Alcohol use likely has some impact on health
  •   May not experience immediate consequences of drinking
  •   May be at risk for social or health problems related to drinking

Low Risk
  •   Alcohol use likely has a small to no impact on health
  •   May have normal drinking habits
  •   May have few, or no, consequences due to drinking

Tip
Ask for permission to share information about health and substance use. Then, review and discuss the reasons the client falls into this risk level and elicit their responses.

Example dialogue #1
"I have some information about substance use and health. Is it okay if I share it with you? You might find the information useful in making decisions about your health."

Example dialogue #2
"Based on your screening results, you are at a high risk for social and medical problems related to substance use. What are your thoughts and feelings about this?"

High Risk

  •   Likely to experience frequent symptoms of addiction to alcohol (e.g. lack of control, withdrawal, tolerance, and physical or psychological problems)

item.text: Are you interested in learning more about what alcohol does to your body?
Discuss the potential medical/physical harms of alcohol use
"What do you think are the possible physical harms alcohol use can have on the body?"

Heavy drinking can increase your risk of developing certain cancers, including cancers of the:
  •   Mouth
  •   Esophagus
  •   Throat
  •   Breast

There is an association between drinking alcohol and developing breast cancer:
  •   Women who consume about one drink per day have a 10% higher chance of developing breast cancer than women who do not drink at all. That risk rises another 10% for every extra drink women have per day.

•   Alcohol irritates the stomach, so heavy drinking can cause an upset stomach and nausea and lead to gastritis. Gastritis occurs when the lining of the stomach becomes inflamed or swollen.
  •   In the longer term, alcohol is associated with an increased risk of cancer of the stomach and bowels.
Regular heavy drinking or heavy drinking on a single occasion is one of the known contributing factors to developing high blood pressure.

Alcohol interferes with the brain's communication pathways. These disruptions can:
  •   Change mood and behavior, increasing the risk of depression and anxiety
  •   Make it harder to think clearly
  •   Make it harder to move with coordination

Drinking a lot over a long time or too much on a single occasion can damage the heart, causing problems including:
  •   Cardiomyopathy (stretching and drooping of heart muscles)
  •   Arrhythmias (irregular heart beat)
  •   A stroke

•   For people with diabetes, alcohol consumption can worsen blood sugar control.
  •   Alcohol causes the pancreas to produce toxic substances that can eventually lead to pancreatitis. Pancreatitis is a dangerous inflammation and swelling of the blood vessels in the pancreas that prevents proper digestion and could lead to development of diabetes.
  •   Heavy drinking takes a toll on the liver, and can lead to a variety of problems and liver inflammations including: Steatosis (or fatty liver), alcoholic hepatitis, fibrosis, cirrhosis, and cancer.

•   Drinking can weaken your immune system, making your body a much easier target for disease.
  •   People who regularly exceed the healthy drinking guidelines are more likely to contract diseases like pneumonia and tuberculosis.
  •   Drinking a lot on a single occasion slows your body's ability to fight infections.

As compared to people who use marijuana on a regular basis, people who don't use find that they:
  •   Have fewer health problems
  •   Have better relationships
  •   Save money
  •   Have fewer problems with work
  •   Are more successful in school and work
  •   Have less risk for depression and anxiety
Are you interested in learning more about what the substance does to your body?
Discuss the potential medical/physical harms of marijuana use
"What do you think are the possible physical harms marijuana use can have on the body?"

Short term
  •   Heavy coughing
  •   Airway inflammation and irritation
  •   Irritation of existing lung illness like asthma or cystic fibrosis

Long term
  •   Increased likelihood of lung infections (pneumonia) and chest illness (bronchitis)

Short term
  •   Short-term memory and motor coordination problems
  •   Difficulty in thinking and problem-solving and loss of coordination
  •   Slowed reaction time
  •   Changed mood, judgment, and decision-making

Long term
  •   Worsen the course of some mental illnesses (e.g., schizophrenia)
  •   Related to depression, anxiety, and lack of motivation

Short term
  •   Speeds up heart rate. It may even double in some cases and can last for hours
  •   Increased risk of heart attack, especially among older adults or those with heart problems

I would like to offer an opportunity to start a conversation about your substance use. What do you think about this idea?
We could start by discussing the pros and cons of changing your substance use or just focus on the benefits of changing. Which option would you like to do?

Tip #1
Discuss the pros of alcohol and/or drug use by asking: "Help me understand from your perspective, what are the good things about drinking or using drugs?"

Tip #2
If you feel that the pros vs. cons activity is not going well, you can ask the client this question instead: "When were you the best version of yourself?" Then: "What would it take to get back to being that person? How does your use of substances play a role in being your best self?"

item.text: Are you interested in learning more about what alcohol does to your body?
Discuss the potential medical/physical harms of alcohol use
"What do you think are the possible physical harms alcohol use can have on the body?"

Heavy drinking can increase your risk of developing certain cancers, including cancers of the:
  •   Mouth
  •   Esophagus
  •   Throat
  •   Breast

There is an association between drinking alcohol and developing breast cancer:
  •   Women who consume about one drink per day have a 10% higher chance of developing breast cancer than women who do not drink at all. That risk rises another 10% for every extra drink women have per day.

•   Alcohol irritates the stomach, so heavy drinking can cause an upset stomach and nausea and lead to gastritis. Gastritis occurs when the lining of the stomach becomes inflamed or swollen.
  •   In the longer term, alcohol is associated with an increased risk of cancer of the stomach and bowels.
Regular heavy drinking or heavy drinking on a single occasion is one of the known contributing factors to developing high blood pressure.

Alcohol interferes with the brain's communication pathways. These disruptions can:
  •   Change mood and behavior, increasing the risk of depression and anxiety
  •   Make it harder to think clearly
  •   Make it harder to move with coordination

Drinking a lot over a long time or too much on a single occasion can damage the heart, causing problems including:
  •   Cardiomyopathy (stretching and drooping of heart muscles)
  •   Arrhythmias (irregular heart beat)
  •   A stroke

•   For people with diabetes, alcohol consumption can worsen blood sugar control.
  •   Alcohol causes the pancreas to produce toxic substances that can eventually lead to pancreatitis. Pancreatitis is a dangerous inflammation and swelling of the blood vessels in the pancreas that prevents proper digestion and could lead to development of diabetes.
  •   Heavy drinking takes a toll on the liver, and can lead to a variety of problems and liver inflammations including: Steatosis (or fatty liver), alcoholic hepatitis, fibrosis, cirrhosis, and cancer.

•   Drinking can weaken your immune system, making your body a much easier target for disease.
  •   People who regularly exceed the healthy drinking guidelines are more likely to contract diseases like pneumonia and tuberculosis.
  •   Drinking a lot on a single occasion slows your body's ability to fight infections.
On a scale of 0 to 10, with 0 being not ready at all and 10 being extremely ready, how likely is it that you will make changes?
I am not sure if I want to make a change
I am ready to make a change
I have already started to change my substance use

If the client is interested in working on their opioid use, ask: "What do you know about the places you can go to get support for stopping opioid use? Can I share additional treatment options with you?"

Based on the assessment results, you are in the medium to high risk range for experiencing problems related to substance use. We are recommending an option that can offer more support than we can. For example, a therapist or a program that offers group therapy and works with you for the long-term. What do you think?
Can I share additional treatment options with you?

Rather than working with professionals, some people may find it more helpful to work with others who have experienced similar challenges. This includes options like Alcoholics Anonymous (AA) or Narcotics Anonymous (NA).
I can help you find a therapist who you can meet with to work on addiction and your goals and the deeper issues that keep it going.

Some addictions can be treated through a rehabilitation program. Often called Rehab, it is a place you stay at for multiple nights. The idea is that you get away from the temptation and spend that time focusing on things that can help you recover, such as therapy.

Some addictions can be treated through what is called IOP. You would go to this program three times a week for three hours each time. You spend much of that time in group therapy and meeting with an individual therapist.

These programs often require you to go daily to get methadone. Methadone helps control your cravings and urges to use. The programs give accountability and may provide extra support from nurses, social workers, and therapists.

Suboxone programs are like visits to your doctor's office. You may be asked to go once a week or once every other week. Suboxone helps control cravings and urges to use. When taken properly, it will block opioids from affecting you.
What do you think? How does that sound?
